=== Low-Dose Naltrexone Studies

Low-dose naltrexone (LDN, 1.5–4.5 mg nightly) has become one of the most widely used off-label treatments for ME/CFS despite limited trial evidence. The proposed mechanism involves transient opioid receptor blockade leading to upregulation of endogenous opioid production and downstream immunomodulation, particularly microglial modulation and restoration of TRPM3 ion channel function in NK cells @Polo2019LDN @Cabanas2021.
Available evidence includes:
    - *Retrospective surveys*: Patient surveys report 50–74% positive response rates, with improvements in fatigue, pain, sleep, and cognitive function. However, retrospective self-report is highly susceptible to bias
    - *Fibromyalgia RCTs*: Two small placebo-controlled RCTs in fibromyalgia (which substantially overlaps with ME/CFS) showed significant pain reduction with LDN @Younger2013. Effect sizes were moderate
    - *NK cell function*: Cabanas et al.\ (2021) demonstrated that naltrexone restores TRPM3 ion channel function in NK cells from ME/CFS patients _in vitro_, providing a plausible immunological mechanism @Cabanas2021
    - *Ongoing RCTs*: Multiple double-blind RCTs are underway (UAB Younger lab dose-finding study, UBC Nacul RCT, LIFT trial combining LDN with pyridostigmine), which should provide definitive efficacy data within 2–3 years


